The most likely issue is that you haven't set the page's `BindingContext` to your ViewModel. Without it, the bindings have nothing to resolve against.

**Fix — set BindingContext in code-behind:**

```csharp
public partial class MyPage : ContentPage
{
    public MyPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = new MyViewModel();
    }
}
```

**Or in XAML:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:YourApp.ViewModels"
             ...>
    <ContentPage.BindingContext>
        <vm:MyViewModel />
    </ContentPage.BindingContext>
    ...
</ContentPage>
```

**Also verify** your ViewModel properties raise `PropertyChanged` (use `INotifyPropertyChanged` or the `[ObservableProperty]` attribute from CommunityToolkit.Mvvm) — otherwise updates after construction won't reflect in the UI.
